            "content": "---\nname: Fix #1806 — --price granularity\ndescription: #1806 (PR #3177) made --price (-I) report the @ transaction price instead of the lot basis\ntype: project\n---\n\n**#1806** (PR #3177): `--price` (`-I`) used to return the lot basis from\nthe amount's annotation, making it indistinguishable from `--basis` (`-B`)\nand hiding realized trading gains/losses in the priced account.  The\nreporter's option roll (sold $1,295 / bought back $1,200 against a\n{{$1,294.20}} basis) showed $0 instead of -$95.\n\nFix in `src/post.cc`, `get_price()`: now prefers `post.given_cost` (the\nuser-typed `@` cost, preserved by the parser) when the annotation price\nis user-supplied.  Posting finalization rewrites `post.cost` to include\n`gain_loss` back to the basis, which is why `post.cost` alone was not\nsufficient.  Falls back to `post.cost` when\n`ANNOTATION_PRICE_CALCULATED` — that branch handles #3009's `@@` total\ncost path where annotation and cost agree by construction.\n\n**Why:** Without this, `-I` was semantically redundant with `-B`; the\nmanual's description of `-I` as \"the price of the commodity purchase\"\nonly makes sense as the @ price, not the lot basis.\n\n**How to apply:** Any future work on `get_price()` should preserve\nthe precedence `given_cost` (user @) > `cost` (when annotation\ncalculated) > `amount.price()` (annotation × quantity).  The third\npath is the no-`@` case \"10 AAPL {$5}\" which has no separate\ntransaction cost.\n\nTests affected (all now reflect corrected semantics):\n- `test/regress/1806.test` (new)\n- `test/baseline/opt-historical.test` (6 `-I` blocks)\n- `test/baseline/opt-price.test` (1 `-I` block)\n- `test/regress/coverage-wave11-report-price-hist.test` (1 `-I` block)\n",
